article.description:
Zaza Pachulia scored on a tip-in with 2.4 seconds left in overtime to help the Atlanta Hawks snap a four-game losing
streak, 108-107 over the Orlando Magic on Sunday.
article.headline: Pachulia tips in Johnson's layup to snap four-game losing streak
article.linkText: Johnson's 40, Pachulia's tip-in lift Hawks in OT
article.story:
ATLANTA (AP) -- Zaza Pachulia was outnumbered down low for most of the game. Still, the Atlanta Hawks' center put up the biggest numbers in the end. Pachulia scored on a tip-in with 2.4 seconds left in overtime to help the Hawks snap a four-game losing streak with a 108-107 win over the Orlando Magic on Sunday. Pachulia, who ranks fourth in the NBA in offensive rebounds, set a career high with 18 boards, including 12 on the offensive end. The final one on the tip-in came after a missed layup by Joe Johnson, who scored 40 points for the Hawks. "I thought Joe had that layup because he was kind of calm," Pachulia said. "Pretty soon I see three guys on him, and one of them was my guy. So I went up and when he missed I was behind to tip. "If Joe scored, I would be just as happy," he said. Forwards Al Harrington and Josh Smith start on the front line with Pachulia, a third-year player in his first season in Atlanta. Harrington and Smith are athletic and versatile inside-outside scorers, but each is only 6-foot-9. The Magic countered with three players 6-foot-10 or taller: Dwight Howard, Tony Battie and Hedo Turkoglu. Each of Orlando's big men scored in double figures, but Magic coach Brian Hill said the 6-foot-11 Pachulia "was the story of the game." With the game on the line in the final seconds of overtime, Hill had a smaller lineup on the floor. "It was a little bit of a mismatch," Hill said. "We had smaller guys and we couldn't keep them off the glass." Johnson, who reached the 40-point mark for the third time this season and added a game-high 11 assists, has been Atlanta's star this season. Harrington added 24 points, but coach Mike Woodson said Pachulia was the main reason the Hawks ended their losing streak. "He's been our workhorse all year," Woodson said. "I've said he's kind of been my MVP because we pretty much have played all year with one big guy. He's done all the dirty work. I'm constantly yelling and screaming at him because I need him. And he responded, big time." Jameer Nelson, who had five points in overtime, missed a last-second jumper for the Magic. Nelson led Orlando, which had eight players score in double figures, with 18 points. Turkoglu added 16 but was called for a key offensive foul with 12.8 seconds left in overtime, setting up the Hawks' game-winning play. It was no surprise the Hawks gave Johnson the chance to win the game. "I was just trying to find an opening," Johnson said. "I was wide open on the baseline and how I missed the layup, I couldn't tell you. I think I was so wide open I didn't realize it." Nelson scored with 2:54 left in the extra session to tie it at 100, and his 3-pointer with 1:24 to play gave Orlando a 105-100 lead. Smith and Johnson answered with 3-pointers for the Hawks. The Hawks couldn't hold a 96-92 lead with 1:16 left in regulation. Nelson's jumper cut the deficit to two and Turkoglu's jumper tied it at 96 -- the eighth tie of the period and 22nd of the game. Following Turkoglu's basket, the Hawks called a timeout with 18.7 seconds left. Johnson worked the clock before passing to Harrington, whose last-second shot bounced off the rim. The Hawks, who trailed most of the first half, leaned heavily on Johnson and Harrington to pull even at 58 at halftime. Johnson, who had 21 points at the break, hit a 3-pointer with 2:41 left. Harrington, who had 14 points in the second period and 18 in the first half, hit two 3-pointers late in the half. Howard finished with 13 points and 15 rebounds. Battie added 14 points. Smith had 15 points and 10 rebounds for Atlanta.

Game notes
The Hawks are 5-2 in overtime games. ... Battie topped his season scoring average with eight points in the first 4:30 of the game. ... Hawks G Salim Stoudamire was taken to the trainer's room late in the third quarter with a sprained right elbow. He did not return to the game.
